    <h2 id="why-digestive-enzymes">Why Digestive Enzyme Gummies Are the Fastest-Growing Supplement Category in Gut Health</h2>

    <p>Digestive enzymes are specialized proteins that break down the food you eat into absorbable nutrients. Your body produces them naturally — amylase in your saliva starts digesting starches before food even reaches your stomach, while pepsin, lipase, and trypsin continue the work in your stomach and small intestine. But enzyme production declines with age, stress, and certain health conditions. A 2019 study in <em>Alimentary Pharmacology and Therapeutics</em> found that up to 30% of adults over 40 produce suboptimal levels of pancreatic enzymes, contributing to bloating, gas, and nutrient malabsorption.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">30%</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">of adults over 40 produce suboptimal levels of pancreatic enzymes, according to research in <em>Alimentary Pharmacology and Therapeutics</em> (2019). This enzyme insufficiency can manifest as chronic bloating, gas, and incomplete digestion — symptoms that supplemental enzyme gummies are designed to address.</p>
    </div>

    <p>The digestive enzyme supplement market reached $1.6 billion in 2025 and is projected to grow at 8.2% annually through 2030, driven by increasing awareness of gut health and the gut-brain axis. Gummy formats have captured a significant share of this market because they solve the compliance problem — many people who need enzyme support find it difficult to swallow large capsules, especially when they are already experiencing GI discomfort. The products on this list deliver clinically meaningful enzyme activity in a format that makes daily use effortless.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Amylase — starch digestion</strong>
        <p>Breaks down complex carbohydrates (bread, pasta, rice) into simple sugars. Without adequate amylase, undigested starches ferment in the colon, producing gas and bloating.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Protease — protein digestion</strong>
        <p>Cleaves protein molecules into amino acids. Insufficient protease can cause protein fermentation in the gut, leading to foul-smelling gas and abdominal discomfort after high-protein meals.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Lipase — fat digestion</strong>
        <p>Emulsifies dietary fats into fatty acids and glycerol. Low lipase activity can cause fatty stools (steatorrhea), bloating after fatty meals, and impaired absorption of fat-soluble vitamins A, D, E, and K.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Cellulase — fiber digestion</strong>
        <p>Humans do not naturally produce cellulase, yet we consume significant plant fiber. Supplemental cellulase helps break down vegetable cell walls, reducing gas from high-fiber meals and improving nutrient extraction.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>A 2018 systematic review in <em>Current Drug Metabolism</em> analyzed <strong>12 clinical trials</strong> and found that oral enzyme supplementation <strong>significantly reduced bloating, gas, and abdominal pain</strong> in individuals with functional dyspepsia and exocrine pancreatic insufficiency. The review noted that multi-enzyme formulas (containing amylase, protease, and lipase) were more effective than single-enzyme products for general digestive support.</p>
      <cite>Current Drug Metabolism, 2018 — 12 clinical trials</cite>
    </div>

    <h3>Why Enzyme Activity Units Matter More Than Milligrams</h3>

    <p>When evaluating digestive enzyme supplements, the critical metric is enzyme activity — not weight. An enzyme's effectiveness depends on how many substrate molecules it can process per unit of time, measured in standardized FCC (Food Chemical Codex) units. A product listing "100mg amylase" tells you nothing about how much starch it can actually break down. The same 100mg could contain anywhere from 5,000 to 50,000 units of activity depending on the enzyme source and concentration. The products on this list were evaluated primarily on their verified enzyme activity levels, not their milligram content.</p>

    <div class="tip-box">
      <span class="tip-box-ico">&#128161;</span>
      <p><strong>Label reading tip:</strong> Look for enzyme activity measured in standardized units: amylase in DU (Dextrinizing Units), protease in HUT (Hemoglobin Units), lipase in FIP (units of lipase activity), and lactase in ALU (Acid Lactase Units). Products that only list milligrams without activity units may be using lower-potency enzyme sources.</p>
    </div>

