    <div class="ing-box">
      <h4>Digestive Enzymes: What the Science Says</h4>
      <p>Digestive enzymes are among the most well-studied supplements in gastroenterology, with decades of clinical research supporting their use in enzyme insufficiency and functional digestive disorders.</p>

      <div class="vs-strip">
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Multi-Enzyme Supplementation</strong>
          <p>A 2018 review in Current Drug Metabolism found that multi-enzyme formulas significantly reduced bloating, gas, and abdominal pain in 12 clinical trials involving patients with functional dyspepsia.<br /><em>Current Drug Metabolism, 2018</em></p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Bromelain for Protein Digestion</strong>
          <p>A 2012 review confirmed bromelain's dual role as a digestive enzyme and anti-inflammatory agent, showing it improved protein absorption and reduced intestinal inflammation.<br /><em>Biotechnology Research International, 2012</em></p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Lactase for Lactose Intolerance</strong>
          <p>Oral lactase supplementation effectively reduces bloating, gas, and diarrhea in lactose-intolerant individuals when taken before dairy consumption.<br /><em>European Review for Medical and Pharmacological Sciences, 2010</em></p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Age-Related Enzyme Decline</strong>
          <p>Pancreatic enzyme output decreases with age, with up to 30% of adults over 40 producing suboptimal levels. This contributes to the increased prevalence of digestive complaints in middle age.<br /><em>Alimentary Pharmacology and Therapeutics, 2019</em></p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

