    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Digestive Enzyme Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What do digestive enzyme gummies actually do?</summary>
      <p>Digestive enzyme gummies supplement your body's natural enzyme production to help break down food more efficiently. They contain enzymes like amylase (starches), protease (proteins), lipase (fats), and cellulase (fiber). When taken before or with meals, these enzymes reduce bloating, gas, and discomfort — particularly after heavy or complex meals.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>When should I take digestive enzyme gummies?</summary>
      <p>Take digestive enzyme gummies immediately before or at the start of a meal. Enzymes need to be present in the stomach when food arrives. Taking them 5-10 minutes before eating allows enzymes to mix with gastric juices before food enters.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are digestive enzyme gummies safe to take daily?</summary>
      <p>For most healthy adults, daily digestive enzyme supplementation is considered safe. However, long-term daily use should be discussed with a gastroenterologist. People with pancreatitis, gallbladder disease, or those taking blood thinners should consult their physician first.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the difference between digestive enzymes and probiotics?</summary>
      <p>Enzymes chemically break down food molecules into absorbable nutrients and work immediately. Probiotics are live beneficial bacteria that colonize the gut and support the microbiome over time. Enzymes address mechanical food breakdown, while probiotics influence long-term gut health. Many people benefit from both.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can digestive enzymes help with lactose intolerance?</summary>
      <p>Yes — specifically the enzyme lactase. Supplemental lactase taken before dairy can significantly reduce bloating, gas, cramping, and diarrhea in lactose-intolerant individuals. Some enzyme blends include lactase; dedicated products like Lactaid are also available.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do digestive enzyme gummies work as well as capsules?</summary>
      <p>Capsules generally deliver higher enzyme activity units per serving, but well-formulated gummies from reputable brands maintain meaningful activity. The primary advantage of gummies is compliance — consistent daily use matters more than marginally higher potency.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Which enzymes should I look for in a digestive enzyme gummy?</summary>
      <p>At minimum: amylase (starches), protease (proteins), lipase (fats), and cellulase (fiber). Bonus enzymes include lactase (dairy), bromelain (pineapple-derived protein enzyme), papain (papaya-derived), and alpha-galactosidase (bean/vegetable gas). Activity should be measured in FCC units, not milligrams.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can children take digestive enzyme gummies?</summary>
      <p>Some enzyme gummies are formulated for children ages 4 and older, but always consult a pediatrician first. Children's digestive systems are still developing, and supplementation should only follow a diagnosed deficiency or condition like lactose intolerance.</p>
    </details>

